The '''Goilalan languages''' are a group of languages placed in the [[Trans–New Guinea languages|Trans–New Guinea]] [[language family|family]] by [[Stephen Wurm]] (1975) and tentatively retained there in the classification of [[Malcolm Ross (linguist)|Malcolm Ross]] (2005). The languages, 
*[[Fuyug language|Fuyug]]
*[[Tauade language|Tauade]]
*Northern (Kunimaipa): [[Biangai language|Biangai]]–[[Kunimaipa language|Kunimaipa]]–[[Weri language|Weri]], 
are clearly related, especially northern Biagai, Kunimaipa, and Weri, which might be considered divergent dialects.  Pronouns are northern 1sg ''ne'', 2sg ''ni'', 3sg ''pi''; Tauade/Fuyug 1sg ''na'', 2sg ''nu'', though Tauade also has the possessive pronouns {{lang|ttd|ne-ve}}, {{lang|ttd|ni-e}}.

