The '''Swedish Institute''' ({{lang-sv|Svenska Institutet}}, {{lang|sv|'''SI'''}}) is a [[Government agencies in Sweden|Government agency in Sweden]] with the responsibility to spread information about [[Sweden]] outside the country. It exists to promote Swedish interests, and to organise exchanges with other countries in different areas of public life, in particular in the spheres of [[culture]], [[education]], and [[research]].<ref>{{cite news|title= Spotlight On: American Swedish Institute |work= [[CBS]]|date=|url= http://minnesota.cbslocal.com/2012/02/27/spotlight-on-american-swedish-institute/|accessdate=2012-03-30}}</ref>
The main office of the Swedish Institute is located in [[Gamla stan]] in central [[Stockholm]]. There is also a branch abroad; the [[Swedish Cultural Centre in Paris]] ({{lang-fr|Centre Culturel Suédois}}). The agency has approximately 90 members of staff and its board is appointed by the [[Government of Sweden]].
In early 2007 the Swedish Institute stated it was planning to set up an "embassy", the "House of Sweden", in [[Second Life]], an Internet-based virtual world. This virtual office is not intended to provide passports or visas, but serve as a point of information about Sweden.<ref>{{cite news | first = | last = | authorlink = | author = [[Agence France-Presse]] | coauthors = | title = Sweden to set up embassy in Second Life | url = http://www.thelocal.se/6219/20070126/ | format = | work = | publisher = thelocal.se | id = | pages = | page = | date = January 26, 2007 | accessdate = January 26, 2012 | language = | quote = }}</ref>
Other Swedish embassies in foreign countries are under the direct authority and control of the [[Ministry for Foreign Affairs (Sweden)|Swedish Ministry of Foreign Affairs]].
== The Twitter account @sweden == {{main article|@sweden}} The Swedish Institute is responsible for the Twitter account @sweden where a new "curator" is selected to tweet every week.
In 2017, SI blocked 14,000 Twitter accounts from interacting with @sweden. Among the blocked were journalists, authors, politicians, businessmen and ambassadors. When the block list was reported in the media, SI lifted the blocks and apologized. <sup>Källa behövs</sup>
When media, with support from the constitutional [[Freedom_of_information_laws_by_country#Sweden|Principle of Public Access]], aked to review the list of blocked accounts the government agency deleted it. <sup>Källa behövs</sup>
